## Secrets Policy (THREE supported mechanisms)

Document in `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` which mechanism the project uses per environment. Never put real secret values anywhere except the secret store itself.

| Mechanism | When to use | How referenced in Mule |
|---|---|---|
| **Env vars → injected as JVM system properties at launch** | Local dev (the `.env` + `scripts/run-mule.ps1` pattern), CI smoke tests | `${sfdc.password}` (NEVER `${env.X}` — see "CRITICAL Mule Property Resolution Gotcha" below) |
| **`secure-properties.yaml`** (encrypted with `secure-properties-tools`) | Shared/committed configs, on-prem, Runtime Fabric, prod-with-keys-in-Vault | `${secure::sfdc.password}` after configuring `<secure-properties:config>` |
| **Anypoint Vault / Runtime Manager Properties tab** | CloudHub 1.0 / 2.0 deployments | `${sfdc.password}` — the property is set per-app in Runtime Manager (mark sensitive ones as **secured** so they're masked) |

The agent MUST ask "where will secrets live for this project?" during init and record the choice **per environment** in `PROJECT_CONTEXT.md` (it can differ between local, CI, and prod).

